The WebTV Client Software

Windows CE is a scalable operating system. It can be configured for each
application. Announced applications include the Handheld PC, the Palm-sized
PC, and the Auto PC. WebTV will use the portions of Windows CE that are most
appropriate for an internet terminal. These include:

   * The Windows CE operating system.
   * A VFAT-compatible file system.
   * A subset of the DirectX 6.0 APIs, including DirectDraw, DirectSound,
     DirectPlay, DirectShow, DirectInput, and Direct3D.
   * Winsock networking API.
   * HTML display capabilities.

The following features will not be a part of the Windows CE for WebTV:

   * The ability to sync with a Windows desktop.
   * The Windows GDI graphics.
   * The Explorer desktop.

The WebTV Service

The WebTV service provides the following features that assist the game
developer:

   * Automated nightly downloads of game code and data.
   * A clean simple UI that allows users to subscribe to games.
   * A clean simple UI that allows users to launch games.
   * Automated nightly uploads of game usage statistics and game crash logs.
   * Backs up and restores users' saved games.

The WebTV Game Development Kit

[Note: This kit should be available by 9/1/98]

This kit includes:

   * A list of third party development software to acquire.
   * Instructions explaining how to configure your development PC.
   * The necessary software libraries to create WebTV applications.
   * The source to a sample game (Doom).

Development System Hardware Requirements

In order to develop a game for WebTV you need the following:

   * A personal computer running Windows 95 / 98 / NT with 128Mb of RAM and
     4Gb of hard disk.
   * A signed NDA with WebTV.
   * A WebTV Plus 5230 Internet receiver.
   * A special parallel port cable to connect your WebTV Plus Internet
     receiver to your PC.

How to Get Started

Developers can get started without any need to wait for WebTV. Just develop
your game to fit the following requirements, and it will probably work quite
well on WebTV:

   * Use up to 4Mb of RAM. (Including code, data, and screen buffers.)
   * 512 x 384 x 16 bpp screen graphics.
   * DirectX 5.0 APIs.
   * MPEG for compressed video.
   * MP2 compressed audio.
   * Use up to 16M bytes of read-only disk file storage. (For the
     application and data).
   * Use up to 32M bytes of read-write scratch-file disk file storage.
   * Use up to 50K bytes of persistent storage (for saved games). This
     storage will be backed up by the WebTV Service.

Differences between a WebTV and a Personal Computer:

   * WebTV has a lower resolution screen (the TV).
   * WebTV has a larger physical screen (the TV).
   * WebTV has less RAM.
   * WebTV has less hard disk.
   * WebTV has no CD-ROM or floppy.
   * WebTV has no mouse.
   * WebTV has relatively few configurations.
   * Automatic installation of software.
   * 100% of users are connected to the WebTV network.

Differences between a WebTV and a Video Game Console:

   * WebTV has a faster processor.
   * WebTV has more RAM.
   * WebTV has a hard disk.
   * WebTV does not have a CD-ROM Drive.
   * Most WebTV users have a keyboard.
   * Many WebTV users have a printer.
   * WebTV does not have a joystick.
   * WebTV may have multiple hardware configurations.
   * 100% of users are connected to the WebTV network.
